<font color="#FF0000">MY STEPFATHER</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jun 17 11:45:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all of you,<br>
My stepfather was stolen from me before I even knew him. I do not speak to him today and probably never will.  He is a <br>
Vietnam Vet, he was in an airborne division, and he enlisted<br>
before he completed his senior year of high school.  His father and grandfather were also veterans, so I think he was<br>
raised to respect that as a right of passage, and maybe that's what sent him away from home.  He was awarded at least three purple hearts that I know of, and I would guess there are other awards I don't remember.  He has watched his best friend from childhood die of Agent Orange.  He met my mom when I was a year old.  He adopted me, as my real father never acknowledged me and did not choose to participate in my life.  He is missing a big chunk of his calf and he has several dark spots in his skin where shrapnel from &quot;The Vietnam Experience&quot; still live to haunt him. I don't know what horror lives in his mind today, but I know he is a &quot;haunted&quot; man.  He drank a lot throughout my youth and was verbally and emotionally abusive to my mother and I since I can remember.  When he came home the last time from Vietnam, the doctor told him he would not be able to have children.  My half-brother is now 24.  I know in my heart now that the reason he favored my brother was that after the hell he lived through, his son was to be the brightest spot in his life.  He used to be a foreman in a major manufacturing facility, but since 1987 he has floated through a few jobs, a divorce from my mother, and now lives with his father and does not work. It is very hard for me to accept the man he has turned into.  He taught me many things in life and for that I am grateful.  After all, it is not every average woman that can say she survived 4 years active duty in The United States Marine Corps and didn't do it on her back! I am VERY proud of my Active Duty Service, and I cam out in 1992 as an E-4(not too shabby, huh?) My stepfather gave me the guts to be a survivor, and now, it's as though he dropped out. I don't know what happened in his mind.  I probably never will because of all the hate that thrives between the two of us.  I've been to The Wall, and cry each time, I visited the Traveling Monument when it was in Batavia,NY, and still it overwhelms me.  I know I can never imagine the pain and disillusionment so many of you suffer, but please know, ther are many in my generation(I'm 27) who know that all you did was pick up the phone when your country came calling, and have to live with the LEFTOVERS from the things you were asked to do in the name of Freedom.<br>
So, from me, Thank You, and God Bless. My thoughts and prayers have been with all of you ever since I was old enough to understand that someone or something stole my stepfather from me before I could even get to know him, much less love him.                           Wendy  
